		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">John Ruskin</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:259px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ruskin.png" class="image" title="Upper: Steel-plate engraving of Ruskin as a young man, made circa 1845, scanned from print made circa 1895. Middle: Ruskin in middle-age, as Slade Professor of Art at Oxford (1869-1879). Scanned from 1879 book. Bottom: John Ruskin in old age, 1894, by photographer Frederick Hollyer. 1894 print. All public domain."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/fe/Ruskin.png" width="257" height="842" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ruskin.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<b>Upper:</b> Steel-plate engraving of Ruskin as a young man, made circa 1845, scanned from print made circa 1895.<br />
<b>Middle:</b> Ruskin in middle-age, as Slade Professor of Art at Oxford (1869-1879). Scanned from 1879 book.<br />
<b>Bottom:</b> John Ruskin in old age, 1894, by photographer <a href="/wiki/Frederick_Hollyer" title="Frederick Hollyer">Frederick Hollyer</a>. 1894 print. All public domain.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>John Ruskin</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1819-02-08"><a href="/wiki/February_8" title="February 8">8 February</a> <a href="/wiki/1819" title="1819">1819</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1900-01-20"><a href="/wiki/January_20" title="January 20">20 January</a> <a href="/wiki/1900" title="1900">1900</a></span>) was a British <a href="/wiki/Art_critic" title="Art critic">art critic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Social_thought" title="Social thought">social thinker</a>, also remembered as an <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a> and <a href="/wiki/Artist" title="Artist">artist</a>. His essays on art and architecture were extremely influential in the <a href="/wiki/Victorian_era" title="Victorian era">Victorian</a> and <a href="/wiki/Edwardian_period" title="Edwardian period" class="mw-redirect">Edwardian</a> eras.</p>
